(117, 1, '2017-07-18 04:15:41', '2017-07-18 04:15:41', '<span class=\"bb-dropcap bb-dropcap--letter\">W</span>hen you type “how to get rid of pores” into Google, over 500,000 results fill your screen. But whilst we’re sorry to disappoint over half a million of you, we want to set the record straight: you <em>cannot</em> get rid of them. And nor should you want to - they’re hair follicles, after all, and they’re normal and natural and entirely necessary. Nevertheless, there are plenty of things you can do to minimise and conceal them – there’s a billion-dollar industry built on pretty much that. Here’s how you do it.\r\n<h2>First line of attack – a good daily skincare regime</h2>\r\nA good skincare regime is the first step in keeping pores in check. They’ll always be there, but there are things you can do to tighten and refine them and to keep them ultra-clean so you don’t suffer from the enlarged, stretched-out pores that blight many a T-zone. If blackheads – effectively blocked pores - are a problem for you, <a href=\"http://www.vogue.co.uk/article/how-to-get-rid-of-blackheads\">see our more extensive guide to tackling them here</a>. But in terms of a regular regime, toners and chemical exfoliators work to refine the skin’s texture – look for glycolic acid and salicylic acid (that’s <a href=\"http://www.vogue.co.uk/article/what-are-ahas-skincare-alphabet\">AHAs</a> and <a href=\"http://www.vogue.co.uk/article/what-is-salicylic-acid-bha-skincare-alphabet\">BHA</a> to the in-the-know) to tighten and brighten. Retinol, too, is a highly effective way to act on pore size. Effectively resurfacing the skin over time, it can shrink the appearance of pores and create a smoother surface – just make sure to follow <a href=\"http://www.vogue.co.uk/article/skincare-alphabet-r-is-for-retinol\">our guide to retinol here</a>, as it often takes time for the skin to get used to it.\r\n<h2>Second line of attack – targeted treatments</h2>\r\nIf you want to take a hard line on pore size or have an event to prepare for at which large pores are not welcome, facialists such as Debbie Thomas and Teresa Tarmey offer laser treatments designed to improve the appearance of the skin and tighten up pores. Peels are also a good way to achieve great temporary pore size reduction – try professional or at-home versions for impressive results. Or for a regular treatment that won’t cost the earth, a clay mask is a great way to draw oil and water out of the pores to shrink their appearance and create a smoother surface (as well as clearing out the imperfections that can lead to congestion and, ultimately, spots).\r\n<h2>Third line of attack – make-up to mask them</h2>\r\nYou may not be able to get rid of your pores, but you can hide them, and a primer is the most effective way. Think of it like an Instagram filter for your skin, blurring pores and creating a smooth finish. A primer will essentially \"fill in\" the pores, making the perfect blank canvas for further make-up. And when it comes to foundation, apply with a Beautyblender sponge to prevent make-up from settling into pores and to ensure even coverage. Finding a formulation that suits you – <a href=\"http://www.vogue.co.uk/gallery/10-best-foundations\">our 10 favourites are here</a> – will create an airbrush-like effect.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-123\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/foxesden/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/810.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"810\" height=\"540\" />\r\n<h3 class=\"c-figure__title\">Alpha-H</h3>\r\nAlpha H Liquid Gold, £33.50. Available at <a href=\"https://www.cultbeauty.co.uk/\">Cultbeauty.co.uk</a>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-122\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/foxesden/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/810-1.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"810\" height=\"540\" />\r\n<h3 class=\"c-figure__title\">Paula\'s Choice</h3>\r\nPaula\'s Choice Clinical 1% Retinol Treatment, £53. Available at <a href=\"https://www.lookfantastic.com/home.dept\">Lookfantastic.com</a>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-121\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/foxesden/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/810-2.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"810\" height=\"540\" />\r\n<h3 class=\"c-figure__title\">Dr. Dennis Gross Skincare</h3>\r\nDr. Dennis Gross Skincare Alpha Beta Peel Original Formula, £70. Available at <a href=\"https://www.cultbeauty.co.uk/\">Cultbeauty.co.uk</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-120\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/foxesden/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/810-3.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"810\" height=\"540\" />\r\n<h3 class=\"c-figure__title\">La Roche-Posay</h3>\r\nLa Roche-Posay Effaclar Sebo-Controlling Mask, £13. Available at <a href=\"http://www.escentual.com/\">Escentual.com</a>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-119\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/foxesden/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/810-4.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"810\" height=\"540\" />\r\n<h3 class=\"c-figure__title\">The Ordinary</h3>\r\nThe Ordinary High Adherence Silicone Primer, £3.90. Available at <a href=\"https://www.cultbeauty.co.uk/\">Cultbeauty.co.uk</a>\r\n<h3><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-118\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/foxesden/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/810-5.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"810\" height=\"540\" /></h3>\r\n<h3 class=\"c-figure__title\">Beautyblender</h3>\r\nBeautyblender Original Foundation Sponge, £16. Available at <a href=\"http://www.selfridges.com/GB/en/\">Selfridges.com</a>', 'Pores, And What To Do About Them', 'There are plenty of things you can do to minimise and conceal them – there’s a billion-dollar industry built on pretty much that. Here’s how you do it.', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'pores-and-what-to-do-about-them', '', '', '2017-07-20 05:07:39', '2017-07-20 05:07:39', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/foxesden/?post_type=beauty-post&#038;p=117', 0, 'beauty-post', '', 0),
