(208, 1, '2017-07-20 06:31:15', '2017-07-20 06:31:15', 'Unlike many people in Hollywood, Courteney Cox is willing to admit that her beauty regime hasn’t always been the most natural. However, the 53-year-old actress has made some changes to her outlook in recent years, telling NewBeauty that aging in the entertainment industry can be as unpleasant as you think, and sometimes you need that one friend who’s willing to tell you to take a breather on the fillers.\r\n<h2>Her <a href=\"http://google.com\">Beauty Regime</a></h2>\r\nAccording to Cox, her usage of facial fillers was slow and steady. “The next thing you know, you’re layered and layered and layered,” she said. “You have no idea because it’s gradual until you go, ‘Oh sh*t, this doesn’t look right.’ And it’s worse in pictures than in real life. I have one friend who was like, ‘Whoa, no more!’ I thought, ‘I haven’t done anything in six months.’ I didn’t realize.”\r\n<blockquote>I feel better because I look like myself. I think that I now look more like the person that I was. I hope I do. Things are going to change.</blockquote>\r\nCox didn’t identify the friend (although we like to imagine it was the ultimate Friend, Jennifer Aniston), but she went on to say that while she may have overdone it, being in the public eye didn’t help. “Hollywood makes [aging] hard; this business makes it harder,” she admitted. “I grew up thinking appearance was the most important thing. That as long as I looked O.K., I would be O.K., which got me into trouble.”\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_103\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"1600\"]<img class=\"wp-image-103 size-full\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/foxesden/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/StockSnap_4FMXU7BTAB.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1067\" /> This is an image caption. Credits can be added here too[/caption]\r\n\r\nAt the behest of her friend, Cox has taken a break from fillers, but stops short of claiming she’s done with them forever. For now, she’s embracing her natural face and wearing minimal makeup.\r\n<blockquote>I feel better because I look like myself. I think that I now look more like the person that I was. I hope I do. <a href=\"http://google.com\">Things are going to change.</a></blockquote>\r\n“I feel better because I look like myself. I think that I now look more like the person that I was. I hope I do. Things are going to change. Everything’s going to drop. I was trying to make it not drop, but that made me look fake,” she said. “You need movement in your face, especially if you have thin skin like I do. Those aren’t wrinkles—they’re smile lines. I’ve had to learn to embrace movement and realize that fillers are not my friend.”\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_105\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"1600\"]<img class=\"size-full wp-image-105\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/foxesden/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/StockSnap_VQSKGNN807.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1060\" /> This is an image caption. Credits can be added here too[/caption]\r\n<h3>Her Beauty Regime</h3>\r\n“I feel better because I look like myself. I think that I now look more like the person that I was. I hope I do. Things are going to change. Everything’s going to drop. I was trying to make it not drop, but that made me look fake,” she said. “You need movement in your face, especially if you have thin skin like I do. Those aren’t wrinkles—they’re smile lines. I’ve had to learn to embrace movement and realize that fillers are not my friend.”', 'A Friend Urged Courteney Cox to Stop Using Facial Fillers', 'The actress told NewBeauty, “I’m as natural as I can be.”', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '101-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-07-20 06:31:15', '2017-07-20 06:31:15', '', 101, 'http://localhost:8888/foxesden/101-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
